12/31/2021: Still busy professionally, so I am falling behind on my radio hobby!  ARRL 10M was a bust, and I was exhausted by the time Stew Perry Top-band Distance Challenge came around so I gave only a superficial effort. Propogation for me just wasn't there, and these are Butt-in-chair (BIC) events. If I am NOT BIC, then I will NOT be around for the propogation. I was not BIC, so no victims here.

End of year operating highlights:

Finally finished WAZ Mixed; VU2TMP Thampi was my hero on 15M CW!
Four all-time-new-ones (ATNO), 70 add'l DXCC Challenge band slots, 8 new DXCC on 60M.
Slowly whittling away at 12 and 17 WAS, with 8 and 2 new ones respectively. It would help if I actually had a "real" antenna for each.
Still don't have AK or HI on 6M, but I DID manage to work EU for the first time on 6M! 45 Grids worked on 6M, finishing 6 shy for the VUCC 300 endorsement.
Seventy-five new WPX prefixes confirmed, putting me at 2162 total. Still need 8 more in Africa to qualify for the WPX Award of Excellence.
Limited exposure multi-transmitter contesting with K4RO and K3IE in 2021...really fun fellows!
This past year has been a slow one as to projects. I made a job change, so I did not make a lot of operating or antenna project time. My priority was health, family, profession this past year. Can I make time for radio projects in 2022? I hope so!

Wishing you all health and happiness in 2022. See you on the bands!

12/05/2021: November is busy contest time! CW SS come and gone at Kirk K4RO's. Fun operation, netting 808 Qs between us under the call K4TCG. I operated at Kirk's on Saturday for the start, then on Sunday I operated under my own call/station for another 375Qs as "fresh meat". I did a casual effort in the SSB SS. I am not practiced at SSB contesting, and I tip my hat to all of the fantastic SSB contest operators I heard/worked. I also did a single-band effort in CQWW CW, having fun expecially with propogation to JA much improved. I was hoping to be able to work/confirm zone 37 to complete WAZ for 15, but the pile-up too deep and me too weak. Lastly, I got to play a little bit in the ARRL 160 contest. I was not able to put BIC (butt-in-chair) for the entire contest, so I had to settle with two two-hour sessions on Saturday evening.

Next contests I am looking forward to are the ARRL 10M and Stew Perry Top-band Distance Challenge. 

Had some nice confirmations to my DXCC, WAZ, and WPX totals as a result of this fall's DXpeditions to the African continent. I am inching my way toward WAZ award of excellence, with only 8 additional African prefixes needed. With my recent award of WAZ, I am now eligable for the 5BWAZ since I have 167 of 200 confirmed. As always, I appreciate the intrepid DXers who travel to far-away (and sometimes dangerous) lands to give DX nerds like me a chance to contact them.

I am delayed in doing any additional antenna work. I started a new job so I have been focused upon that priority instead of radio. I did manage to cobble together a feedbox for my full-time Inverted L but I am not happy with it. I am currently in my 160M winter configuration: My rebuilt G5RV voltage-fed as a Marconi over 1500 feet total on-ground radials, using an autotuner. I should have one of the two 40M dipoles up on the trees in the next week or so. 

11/05/2021: CW SS will be a casual-ish multi-two effort at Kirk K4RO's place, activating the Tennessee Contest Group's call K4TCG. Casual-ish simply because me and Kirk can't really be casual about contesting, so let's just agree that it will be a time-limited operation. All Qs will be appreciated, so please contact us if you hear us. I will probably be active as my own call on as Sunday "fresh meat."

Had fun chasing the recent DXpeditions in October: J5HKT, S9OK, 3DA0RU, 7P8RU. I am happy to add three more prefixes to my WPX totals for Africa toward my WPX Award of Excellence and to add to my 60M country totals. Great DXpeditions, great operators. Many thanks to the teams! 

I am delayed in doing any additional antenna work. Big plans, poor time management. I started a new job so I have been focused upon that priority instead of radio. So many radio projects that need my attention (am I right?)

10/17/2021 -- Overhauled my primary doublet (G5RV) that I have in place primarily for 80M. It is now up at approx. 60' AGL. Thinking about a small L-match instead of using my rig's tuner. That said, the impedance load is pretty easy for my IC-7600's tuner.

I also overhauled my 160M inverted-L (more like an inverted U). It modeled well in EZNEC, using about 150' total wire. Seems to function fine, but will need a few more hours on it. I have a large 14x14" plastic utility box at the feedpoint, with the intention of putting in the required capacitors and inductors, along with control circuitry. This is a work-in-progress.

Still needed is getting my 40M dipole up higher. I better hurry...CW Sweepstakes is coming up soon!

9/28/2021 -- Many MANY thanks to Thampi VU2TMP for working me on 15M this morning! Confirmed via LoTW a few minutes later for ATNO and Zone 22, completing WAZ! I am very happy, and I am grateful to Thampi for making time for the contact and his patience while we completed the QSO. 73 my friend for the new one!

I have not been very active due to my professional schedule. Recently, I joined K3IE at K4RO's QTH to activate K4TCG during the Tennessee QSO Party. I really enjoy operating with these gentlemen, and as always K4RO's station is top-notch.

I've also been experimenting with the Radioberry and Hermes-Lite SDR projects with great interest. It is such a different world compared to conventional "radios", and these little projects have been a wonderful introduction into the modern SDR architectures along with exercising some long-dormant programming skills!

I was not able to operate 6M at all during the August tail-end of the Summer Es. I was fortunate to add a few more EU stations during the nice July opening: G, GM, OX, SM...magic band! VUCC confirmed is sitting at 294 currently, and though I had hoped to finish with 300 confirmed by the end of this sporadic E season, you cant work them if you are not on the radio. I am grateful for every Q I am able to make these days.

Lastly, I am in process of overhauling my wire antennas, and hopefully will be back the low-bands very soon.

5/20/2021 First EU on 6M ever! Thanks to MM0AMW & EI4KF for the great ears! Also 4U1UN...Awesome 6M Es (sporadic E) propogation toward EU today. Barefoot and a little 2-el up 10M AGL! S5, CU, G, MD also heard by not worked...yet.

(Excited to put up a "real" antenna for 6m!)

Some additional fun to brag (sorry) about. The recent A25RU/C92RU expeditions, and 7X3WPL gave me three ATNO and three more African prefixes. I am excited that I am only ten AF prefixes from qualifying for the WPX Award of Excellence. Thanks all!

3/31/21 - Slowly making progress on getting my antenna wires up higher in my trees. 10 years of growth made for 20-30' more usable height! So far I have an Inv-L and 80M doublet up to at least 55'. Looking at 40M next. Hope to work you soon!

12/27/2020: Thanks to all for the Qs throughout this year. We have been fortunate here in that we have remained healthy and have wanted for nothing. So many others have had it SO rough, locally and around this world. I try to keep this foremost in my thoughts.

I have not done my year-end record keeping but there are several highlights:

Team K3LR in ARRL DX CW in February
30M completed for 6BDXCC
CWOps Anniversary callsign activation
Fun contests: Tennessee QSO Party, ARRL 160, Stew Perry Top Band Distance Challenge (even dropped into a NAQP Sprint!)
Wishing everyone a very healthy, very happy, very peaceful 2021!

11/15/2020: Turning my attention toward the low-bands, perhaps a little late for this season. Revamping/moving VE3DO RX loop, considering other options for more directions. Looking wisftully up into the now bare trees thinking about which branch I can a) get a slingshot over and b) will support doublets and ends of vertical wires. 

Also enjoying a bit of TEP on 10M, and some MS on 6M. Amazing propogation modes!

Did a meh sort of job in SS CW last. It was a brain thing, I think. Talked it over with a few contesting friends and found I was not alone. All in all, I am still grateful to have been able to participate, things as they are.

Stay healthy and sane everybody!

9/7/2020: Worked 50 more grids on 6M during this sporadic E season, fair progress considering my compromise antenna and lack of time due to professional committments. Two more to confirm and I will apply for the 250 grid VUCC sticker.
Had fun in the TNQP on 9/6/2020 with a pretty good result. QSO Parties are fun! If you have never participated in one, give it a try! Look here for a schedule of what's coming up: WA7BNM Contest Calendar.

6/13/2020: Got the IC-7600 back from SAR Technical Services. Great work and fast turn-around! Just in time for Sporadic E season on 6M. Still DX to be had on 60M. Currently at 84 countries worked, 73 confirmed on 60M.

Stay healthy and sane everybody!

4/11/2020: Just received confirmation from ZK3A for country #100 on 30M. Now I can apply for the medalion for to add to my 5BDXCC plaque. No, I dont have a resonant 30M antenna although I really should for this fantastic band, and that's why it took me so long! 

I still have not sent my IC-7600 in for repair (pandemic and all). I miss 60M and I am stalled at 65 countries until I get a rig that functions on the band. If that's all I have to complain about during these trying times then I remain fortunate! 

Stay healthy and sane everybody!

2/25/2020: For my birthday, I made a donation to Team Exuberance CW 2020 to help get the team to K3LR's super station for the CQWW WPX CW 2020 contest. Find their GoFundMe campaign page and spot them a few bucks. These youth are some of the best emerging contesting talent regardless of age. Help give them world-class experience by supporting their next effort!

2/22/2020: Welcome France to 60M! I am happy to have logged F5NBQ for my first French QSO. Also worked: F6BLP, F5BZB, F5II. Now at 61 countries on 60M...thanks for the new one!

2/1/2020: I have just reached a milestone that is very important to me and my little station! I just received enough LoTW confirmations that I may apply for the ARRL DXCC Challenge award! 

I have currently 1025 "band slots" confirmed from countries on 160M through 10M. I so appreciate all those intrepid DXpeditioners with superb ears who have pulled my little signal out of the noise!

My next challenge is the CQ WPX Award of Excellence...I need to confirm just 18 15 more prefixes from Africa and I will be able to apply.

1/2/2020: My end of year stats are below. 99% of these contacts were made with 100W power output using doublets (for low bands) or a 2 element yagi (for the high bands), nothing higher than 35' AGL. I offer this as encouragement for anyone who has similar station limitations:

DXCC totals on 60M are NOW at an even 65 countries confirmed! I worked WAS as well. 60M is a fantastic band with surprising world-wide progagation!
Confirmed 1000+ band slots to qualify for DXCC Challenge. I added 144 confirmed country/bands to put me over the 1000 mark.
I added 24 all-time new ones ("ATNO") to put me at 236 countries confirmed on LoTW.
I added 3 new countries on 160M to put me at 51 confirmed. This remains one of my greatest DX challenges. 
18 ZERO additional countries toward my 30M DXCC, leaving only 3 more to go DONE! I can apply for my medallion to go on my 5BDXCC plaque.
I am still whittling away at WAS on 30,17,12 and 6M. I need AK and HI on 6M for WAS, and hope to accomplish this during the summer 2020 Sporadic E season. Note to self: Replace 2-element yagi with something bigger before June 2020! 
I like to collect grid squares for VUCC, currently on 6M and satellites. I have not been terribly active on the sats recently. Last year I confirmed 20+ new 6M grids and received my 200 grid VUCC endorsement.
I track unique prefixes as well, and working toward my CQ WPX Award of Excellence. I have only 18 16 more unique prefixes to confirm in Africa to be eligable. I have confirmed 175 new prefixes this year, and am sitting at 2002 mixed band/mode prefixes confirmed via LoTW.
And for Worked All Zones, MY KINGDOM FOR ZONE 22! When I confirm a contact in zone 22, I will be able to apply for WAZ mixed AND be eligable to apply for the starting level of 5BWAZ. I may need to do some optimization in 2020 specifically for the purpose of working/confirming zone 22!
I had 7009 QSOs over 2019, not counting my guest operations (thanks guys!) at K3LR and K4RO. No operations in the Carribbean this year (sadface emoji here.) The last half of the decade I have had professional obligations that limit my radio time. You can't work them if you are not at the radio! Health, family, and profession ALL take precident over amateur radio!

12/28/2019: I experienced this noise all evening during the Top Band Distance Challenge!



I was listening using a VE3DO loop pointed E. I tweaked my blanker settings for lowest noise, and used just enough noise reduction to take the roaring away. Finally I had to set my bandwidth to a minimum--100hz or so. Even at 150hz the noise was S5 as you can see. Ah yes, city life.

Of course, the noise on the transmit antenna was even worse, so thank goodness for a receive antenna!
